Background

This assignment will make use of an external data set, i.e. a data set that you have to upload to R yourself. We will do this using the readr package, which is part of the core tidyverse and assists in reading/writing files. You will be working with a file called "sparrows.csv". You will see this file is available already in this project in the Files pane in RStudio. If you click on this file name, it will appear in the Editor pane - this is a comma-separated file (CSV, comma-separated values), meaning each column of data is separated by a comma. Another way to say this is that the file is comma-delimited. It is also very common to see tab-delimited files (TSV) in data science.

Data in this file was collected in 1898 by Hermon Bumpus, an American biologist working at Brown University. Immediately following a bad winter storm, he collected 136 English house sparrows (some alive, some dead), Passer domesticus, and brought them indoors. Of these birds, 64 had died during the storm, but 72 recovered and survived. Bumpus measured the birds’ physical traits and recorded them for future generations of data science students.

Reading CSV files and defining factors

We use the function read_csv from the package readr to read in CSV files. When using functions from specific packages, it is often safer to write them in the format package::function(), i.e. readr::read_csv(), just in case there is another function named readr() also floating around in the R environment. It is not likely this will happen to you at this stage of your data sciencing, but it doesn’t hurt to get in the habit.

We can read in the file as follows:

## save the data frame, automatically made into a
## TIBBLE by readr, into the variable `sparrows`
## readr tells us about all the columns it reads
## in!!
sparrows <- read_csv("data/sparrows.csv")  ## RELATIVE PATH to the dataset
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Sex = col_character(),
##   Age = col_character(),
##   Survival = col_character(),
##   Length = col_double(),
##   Wingspread = col_double(),
##   Weight = col_double(),
##   Skull_Length = col_double(),
##   Humerus_Length = col_double(),
##   Femur_Length = col_double(),
##   Tarsus_Length = col_double(),
##   Sternum_Length = col_double(),
##   Skull_Width = col_double()
## )

readr has made some very educated guesses as to what type of variable each column stores - it has found three character columns, and nine double columns. Doubles can be thought of numbers with decimals, as opposed to integers - we therefore know these columns contain continuous quantitative data! (Note: it is possible to specify the column types to readr, but that’s for another day.)

Let’s examine the actual values further:

## Examine the data
head(sparrows)
## # A tibble: 6 x 12
##   Sex   Age   Survival Length Wingspread Weight Skull_Length Humerus_Length
##   <chr> <chr> <chr>     <dbl>      <dbl>  <dbl>        <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Male  Adult Alive       154        241   24.5         31.2           17.4
## 2 Male  Adult Alive       160        252   26.9         30.8           18.7
## 3 Male  Adult Alive       155        243   26.9         30.6           18.6
## 4 Male  Adult Alive       154        245   24.3         31.7           18.8
## 5 Male  Adult Alive       156        247   24.1         31.5           18.2
## 6 Male  Adult Alive       161        253   26.5         31.8           19.8
## # … with 4 more variables: Femur_Length <dbl>, Tarsus_Length <dbl>,
## #   Sternum_Length <dbl>, Skull_Width <dbl>

From the head(sparrows) output, we see that those three character columns appear to contain categories of a categorical variable. In R, we use the data type factor to represent categorical variables, and we call the categories levels. But, R doesn’t seem to think that these columns are factors - it thinks they are characters - plain old works with nothing interesting linking them.

In fact, readr assumes that NOTHING is a factor, so we have the full power to determine which variables are factors, and what the order of the categories should be. In R, we call the categories of a factor its levels. While factors are very meaningful, they can be frustrating to work with. Trust me.

The base R version of the read_csv function is read.csv and assumes the opposite - that all characters are factors. This problem notoriously causes everyone a lot of major headaches because factors are very difficult to work with.

Let’s therefore begin to convert these columns into factors:

### Convert Sex to a factor
sparrows$Sex <- factor(sparrows$Sex)

### If we run head() again, we'll see the successful
### change
head(sparrows)
## # A tibble: 6 x 12
##   Sex   Age   Survival Length Wingspread Weight Skull_Length Humerus_Length
##   <fct> <chr> <chr>     <dbl>      <dbl>  <dbl>        <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Male  Adult Alive       154        241   24.5         31.2           17.4
## 2 Male  Adult Alive       160        252   26.9         30.8           18.7
## 3 Male  Adult Alive       155        243   26.9         30.6           18.6
## 4 Male  Adult Alive       154        245   24.3         31.7           18.8
## 5 Male  Adult Alive       156        247   24.1         31.5           18.2
## 6 Male  Adult Alive       161        253   26.5         31.8           19.8
## # … with 4 more variables: Femur_Length <dbl>, Tarsus_Length <dbl>,
## #   Sternum_Length <dbl>, Skull_Width <dbl>
### The levels function tells us the categories in
### the variable:
levels(sparrows$Sex)
## [1] "Female" "Male"

By definition, levels are ordered, and if no order is specified, R defaults to alphabetical order. To re-order a factor, simply refine the levels with your preferred order of the categories, for example:

### Make the order Male, Female.
levels(sparrows$Sex) <- c("Male", "Female")

## Print it out to see
print(levels(sparrows$Sex))
## [1] "Male"   "Female"

This can also all be done at once with the single command below.

### Convert to factor and order levels as desired at
### once
sparrows$Sex <- factor(sparrows$Sex, levels = c("Male", 
    "Female"))

Question 2

You may have noticed in Question #1, Alive was automatically plotted before Dead. What if we wanted Dead before Alive on the X-axis? We’d have to re-factor the column!. For this question, do the following:

  • Use your new factor skills to convert both Survival and Age to factors. For Survival, set the order to be be (1) Dead, (2) Alive. for Age, the order should be (1) Young, (2) Adult.
    • In total, this should be two lines of code only (one line for each variable) - in a single line, you should set the variable as a factor AND define its levels.
    • Confirm you are correct by printing the LEVELS of each column
  • Then, make a new barplot visualizing Survival with your re-factored variable to see how the X-axis order changed.
sparrows$Survival <- factor(sparrows$Survival, levels = c("Dead", 
    "Alive"))  ##Makes survival a factor rather than a character, Dead or Alive are now LEVELS.
print(levels(sparrows$Survival))  ##Shows the results of the function above.
## [1] "Dead"  "Alive"
sparrows$Age <- factor(sparrows$Age, levels = c("Young", 
    "Adult"))
print(levels(sparrows$Age))
## [1] "Young" "Adult"
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Survival)) + geom_bar(width = 0.7, 
    fill = "darkmagenta") + labs(y = "Count", x = "Survival") + 
    theme_bw()

Question 3

We will now look at the relationship between two categorical variables using a grouped bar plot. Visualize the distribution of Survival using a bar plot as before, but now color (in this case, fill) the bars by Age. There are two ways these bars can be represented: stacked (this will happen by DEFAULT when you add the fill) or dodged (add the argument position = "dodge" to geom_bar()).

Make one of each type of barplot, and in the space below, answer whether Young or Adult sparrows were more likely to survive. Write an additional 1-2 sentences describing which visualization choice makes it easier to answer this question.

stacked1 <- ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Survival, fill = Age)) + #Defined this plot as a variable for the next question, same is done below.
  geom_bar(width = 0.7) + #Automatically applies the stacked barplot, no coding required.
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightcyan3", "darkorange4")) +
  labs(y = "Count", x = "Survival") +
  theme_bw()
print(stacked1)

dodged1 <- ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Survival, fill = Age)) +
  geom_bar(width = 0.7, position = "dodge") + #Adjusting this position will separate the bars.
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lavenderblush3", "hotpink4")) +
  labs(y = "Count", x = "Survival") +
  theme_bw()
print(dodged1)

While both visualization choices are easy to interpret I believe that the latter option, a dodged barplot, is easier to read. With a quick once-over I can tell that the adult sparrows are morelikely to survive.

Question 6

We will now learn to make a faceted plot, which splits your figure into a row or grid of panels highlighting different subsets of the data. Our goal is to re-make the density plot from Question 5, but faceting by sex: This means there will be one plot for Males and one plot for Females (ordered by factor level!!). There are two functions that can accomplish this: facet_wrap() and facet_grid(); the latter is most useful for faceting multiple variables.

  • Consider this simple example of visualizing iris sepal lengths faceted by Species, using the function facet_wrap():

    ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + geom_density() + 
    facet_wrap(~Species)  ## the tilde!! so important!! Pronounced as 'across' or 'by', as in: facet across species, or facet by species

Now, redo your plot from Question 5 so that it is faceted by Sex. In the space below, write 2-4 sentences about whether considering sex separately when plotting helped you to understand trends in the data. What trends do you now see that you didn’t see before, if any? What trends are new?

ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Skull_Width, fill = Survival)) + 
    geom_density(alpha = 0.4) + scale_fill_manual(values = c("coral3", 
    "powderblue")) + theme_bw() + labs(x = "Skull Width", 
    y = "Density") + facet_wrap(~Sex)

After facteting these images it appears that skull width DOES have an influence on survival when sex is also considered. Male sparrows with thinner beaks have a higher survival rate than those with thicker beaks. Additionally, females do not show this trend.

Question 10

We will now recreate the scatterplot to include a line of best fit (also known as regression line) with the additional geom, geom_smooth(method = "lm") (don’t worry about its specific method="lm" argument yet, just know you should use it right now). We will want to color the points by Sex, as before. Perform this task below in TWO WAYS:

  • Place the aesthetic mapping to color within the geom_point() call
  • Place the aesthetic mapping to color within the overall ggplot() call (along with X and Y specs).

In the space below, explain why the lines of best fit (aka regression lines) look different between the two plots, and what each line represents in each plot. In addition, based on your figures, do you think males and females have fundamentally different RELATIONSHIPS between skull width and length?

ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Skull_Length, y = Skull_Width)) +

    scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "orange")) + 
    theme_bw() + labs(x = "Skull Length", y = "Skull Width")

ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Skull_Length, y = Skull_Width,

Each of the regression lines were different in these plots as the location of the aes(color = Sex) changes, when the code is within the the geom_point() there is a single trendline for the entire dataset. When the code is placed within the ggplot() there are two trendlines per sex. Although these trends vary slightly in their slope it doesn’t appear there is a significant difference in these regression lines.

## Fix the code above in this chunk.

Question 15

We can also learn to change how points are displayed: by default they are dots that can be colored but not filled. It turns out there are many types of shapes that R accepts. The default shape in ggplot is 19. Importantly, point types 21-25 can BOTH be colored (eg black outline) and filled (eg the blue fill).

R point options

Practice specifying two new types of shapes, one that CAN NOT be filled and one that CAN BE filled, in a scatter plot of Skull Width vs Skull Length below. Specify your shape like this: geom_point(shape=...) where ... is the number shape.

ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Skull_Length, y = Skull_Width, 
    color = Sex, fill = Sex)) + geom_point(shape = 23) + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm") + scale_color_manual(values = c("olivedrab", 
    "royalblue3")) + scale_fill_manual(values = c("seashell3", 
    "darkgrey")) + theme_bw() + labs(x = "Skull Length", 
    y = "Skull Width")

### Scatterplot with type of point NOT
### 21,22,23,24,25. Specify a color (not aesthetic -
### just straight up color the points)
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x = Skull_Length, y = Skull_Width, 
    color = Sex)) + geom_point(shape = 8) + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
    scale_color_manual(values = c("tomato", "steelblue4")) + 
    theme_bw() + labs(x = "Skull Length", y = "Skull Width")
